@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

<> a schema:CreativeWork ;
    schema:name "owl:sameAs vs skos:related — LOD cross-reference predicate selection"@en ;
    schema:description "Decision algorithm for choosing owl:sameAs or skos:related when linking KG entities to DBpedia/Wikidata equivalents."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-15T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:about :owlSameAsVsSkosRelatedGuide .

:owlSameAsVsSkosRelatedGuide a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "owl:sameAs vs skos:related predicate selection guide"@en ;
    schema:description "Step-by-step rule for deciding which RDF predicate to use when cross-referencing a KG entity with a DBpedia or Wikidata resource."@en ;
    schema:step :step1, :step2, :step3, :step4 .

:step1 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 1 ;
    schema:name "Verify the LOD IRI"@en ;
    schema:text "Confirm the DBpedia or Wikidata IRI actually exists (HTTP 200 or Wikidata label-search result). Never fabricate or assume an IRI. If unconfirmed, omit the cross-reference entirely."@en .

:step2 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 2 ;
    schema:name "Ask: does this entity co-denote the same individual?"@en ;
    schema:text """Ask the identity question: is the KG entity IRI just another name for the exact same thing as the DBpedia/Wikidata IRI?

Use owl:sameAs if YES — the two IRIs are aliases for the same individual:
- A KG entity representing SPARQL the query language → owl:sameAs dbpedia:SPARQL
- A KG entity representing Markdown the format → owl:sameAs dbpedia:Markdown
- A KG entity representing Linked Data → owl:sameAs dbpedia:Linked_data
- A KG entity representing Git the VCS → owl:sameAs dbpedia:Git
- A KG entity representing data provenance → owl:sameAs dbpedia:Provenance_(information_science)
- Person platform IRIs for the same person (LinkedIn, X, Substack) → owl:sameAs

Use skos:related if NO — the entity is about, illustrates, wraps, or is contextually associated
with the LOD concept, but is not the same individual:
- A schema:ListItem describing the advantage of IRI-based identity → skos:related dbpedia:IRI
- A schema:ListItem describing federation as a capability → skos:related dbpedia:Federated_database
- A schema:PropertyValue capturing a dimension of a comparison → skos:related the compared concept
- A DefinedTerm describing a problem that is similar to but not identical to a LOD concept"""@en .

:step3 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 3 ;
    schema:name "Consider the RDF type as a signal"@en ;
    schema:text """The RDF type of the entity is a strong signal:

Types that OFTEN warrant owl:sameAs (when the entity IS the named concept):
- schema:DefinedTerm, skos:Concept, schema:SoftwareApplication, schema:Language,
  schema:TechArticle — when the term directly names a well-known LOD-resolvable concept

Types that RARELY warrant owl:sameAs (the entity is usually a wrapper or description):
- schema:ListItem, schema:PropertyValue, schema:ItemList — these describe, compare, or list
  concepts; they are almost never the same individual as the concept they mention

Exception: a schema:ListItem whose name and description are entirely about one named standard
(e.g., name='SPARQL', description='SPARQL provides SELECT…') can still warrant owl:sameAs
if it genuinely co-denotes that standard rather than describing an advantage of it."""@en .

:step4 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position 4 ;
    schema:name "When in doubt, prefer skos:related"@en ;
    schema:text "owl:sameAs has strong entailment consequences in OWL reasoners — all properties of one individual are inherited by the other. If unsure whether the entities are truly co-referential, use skos:related. It is semantically accurate for associative relationships and carries no unintended entailments. Upgrade to owl:sameAs only when identity is unambiguous."@en .
